metadata.name: SETNAS #190
metadata.description:
SETNAS

-NOTES:

-100% code generated (no images or sounds preloaded)

-'Click' to START/pause.

-Save current frame to PNG-> press 'S' or  drag on top of screen.

-Save 2 s. animation to GIF-> press 'G' or drag on bottom of screen.

-All audio stuff is done with WebPd.

-All visual is done with p5js.

-Chrome browser recommended

-Headphones recomended. Some extreme sounds (frequency and amplitude) can be generated.

-Supply can be halved/reduced and/or the price can be doubled if all iterations have not been minted (every 24h aprox).

DESCRIPTION:

-An audiovisual piece based on randomly generated patterns. These patterns generate endless unique pieces of electronic music (and their corresponding visuals).

-This is a 16-step sequencer based on 2 basic patterns: the kick drum and the tuplets of each kick.

-In each cycle (from 16 to 64 kicks) there can be changes to many of the parameters of the patterns, thus generating changes to the piece in an infinite way.

FEATURES:

-"tipusGrid": type of grid-> (lines, rects, soroll (noise), ASCII, mosaic or barcode).
-"baseShape": first cicle base shape (rect, circle,lines, vlines or hlines).
-"baseSize": size of base shape.
-"gridDensity": grid size (16, 32 or 64).
-"alpha": alpha of base image.
-"alpha2": alpha of canvas.
-"darkMode": dark mode (true) or light mode (false).
-"color": color of lines (dark mode) or background (light mode)-> white, red, green or blue.
-"bpm": Beats Per Minute. from 90 to 160 -> this value is theoretical, some devices may not be able to play the piece at a certain speed.
-"tipusBass": type of bass drum (from 0 to 5).
-"maxTuplet": max number of tuplets for each kick.
-"reverb": has reverb effect (audio)

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #711
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Sabler : Serengeti #162
metadata.description:
'Sabler : Serengeti' is a special edition reissue of the original Sabler generator in a vibrant 'Serengeti' palette which was omitted from the original collection. 

Towards the end of the production of the original Sabler collection, the creative decision was made to reduce the number of palettes from the thirteen that had been created to a smaller number, in order to improve the cohesiveness of the collection overall. While 'Serengeti' remained one of the stronger palettes, it was ultimately excluded in favour of the 'Annaliese' palette, in homage to an Anni Albers tapestry that originally inspired the 'Sabler' collection. 

Here, the 'Serengeti' palette is provided as a companion piece to the original Sabler collection to give collectors the opportunity to pair their output with their existing collection if they choose.

Below follows an edited description for the original 'Sabler' collection:

'Sabler', an anagram of 'Albers', is a generative homage to the work of the Bauhaus textile artist Anni Albers.

The aesthetic of this piece and its proportions are guided by the Golden Ratio (1.618 : 1) and as such, each part of the composition relates in some way to its larger self.

As lines playfully extend and overlap one another from various grid segments, patterns appear, 'ghost' shadings emerge and complexity is implied even with the use of very simple elements.

There are no rarities or special features, other than for you to enjoy the unique qualities of your piece!

You can save a high resolution 3000px x 3000px PNG of your edition by pressing the 'S' key.

metadata.name: Travelling Gondola #35
metadata.description:
The Traveler says:

-Each planet has a story, in this gondola you can talk to the stars, confess to the moon... I've seen the beginning and end of ages, slowly... slowly I travel and witness the passage of everything, I'm in no hurry if time is slower than me, and one day we will reach the singularity.

Is it the end?

-

Interactivity:

[ARROW UP] - Ticket Up.
[ARROW DOWN] - Ticket Down.
[MOUSE HOVER ON TICKET] - Shows what each feature defines.

[A] - Render a 20 frames gif.
[S] - Render a 40 frames gif.
[D] - Render a 60 frames gif.
 
[Z] - Save a printscreen of canvas.
[X] - Up/Down ballons.
[C] - Open/Close blueprint.

-

Travelling Gondola have 7 Features:
-Gunwale
-Hull Sides
-Hull Middle
-Biome
-Superficie
-Vegetation
-Atmosphere



by Gen Doodler | twitter.com/GenDoodler

metadata.name: Soft Cell #64
metadata.description:
This work is an homage to relief printmaking. Other artists have explored the kinship between generative art and print using pen plotters and silkscreen. This work attempts to take the concept of a relief print and apply it to a digital canvas.

This art work is produced in layers. For each layer the printing surface or matrix is defined by one set of algorithms. Another set of algorithms then applies the "ink" (imperfectly!) to the matrix. For each layer in turn the matrix is then applied to the canvas.

Press [s] to save a png image of the work.

The work renders at an economical 800x800px. Any edge size may be specified by adding &sz=x to the URL. A print of about 6 inches by 6 inches is recommended, &sz=1800 at 300dpi.

Rust/JS/WASM
Polygon SDF algorithm adapted from Inigo Quilez.
